================================================================
STEP UP EDITOR — FULL PROJECT BLUEPRINT
A drag-and-drop UI editor for event greetings, invitations,
and party systems. This document is the master reference for
planning, hiring, and building the product.
================================================================


----------------------------------------------------------------
1. WHAT WE'RE BUILDING — ONE PARAGRAPH
----------------------------------------------------------------

A web app where a non-technical user drags elements (text,
images, countdowns, buttons, effects) onto a canvas, customizes
them through a side panel, and clicks "Get Link" — which
generates a real, animated, interactive HTML page, uploads it
to a hosting service automatically, and hands back a shareable
URL. No coding knowledge required from the end user.

Think: Canva, but the output is a living interactive web page
instead of a flat image, and the niche is event UI (invitations,
greetings, party dashboards) instead of general graphic design.


----------------------------------------------------------------
2. THE FOUR SYSTEMS — HIGH LEVEL
----------------------------------------------------------------

  SYSTEM A — THE EDITOR (frontend)
    What the user sees and interacts with. Drag-and-drop canvas,
    element library, properties panel, live preview.

  SYSTEM B — THE DATA LAYER (storage)
    Where a user's in-progress and finished projects are saved,
    so they can leave and come back, or edit later.

  SYSTEM C — THE GENERATOR (backend logic)
    Converts a saved project (structured data) into a real,
    standalone HTML file with working animations and interactions.

  SYSTEM D — THE PUBLISHER (hosting integration)
    Takes the generated HTML file, sends it to a hosting API
    (Netlify), and returns a live shareable URL to the user.


----------------------------------------------------------------
3. TECH STACK — WHAT LANGUAGE FOR WHAT PART
----------------------------------------------------------------

  SYSTEM A — THE EDITOR (frontend)
  --------------------------------
  Core language    : JavaScript (or TypeScript — recommended,
                      see note below)
  Framework        : React
                      (most common choice for drag-and-drop
                      editors — huge ecosystem, easy to hire for)
  Drag-and-drop    : A library, not built from scratch —
                      "dnd-kit" or "react-dnd" are the standard
                      choices. Building drag-and-drop physics by
                      hand is a waste of time when solved
                      libraries exist.
  Styling          : CSS or Tailwind CSS
                      (Tailwind speeds up building UI panels —
                      optional but common in modern teams)
  State management : React's built-in state is enough at first.
                      If the app grows complex, "Zustand" is a
                      lightweight option (simpler than Redux).

  NOTE ON TYPESCRIPT:
  TypeScript is JavaScript with safety rails — it catches
  mistakes before they become bugs. For a project this size
  with a team (not solo), TypeScript is worth the small extra
  learning curve. Recommend hiring developers who already know
  it, or budget time for the team to use it from day one.


  SYSTEM B — THE DATA LAYER (storage)
  ------------------------------------
  In-progress drafts : Browser's own storage (localStorage or
                        IndexedDB) — no server needed for this
                        part. Free, simple, already built into
                        every browser.
  Saved projects      : A real database, once a user wants to
                        keep something permanently and access
                        it later from any device.
  Database choice     : "Supabase" or "Firebase"
                        Both are "backend as a service" — they
                        give you a real database, user accounts,
                        and file storage without needing to
                        build or manage your own server.
                        Supabase uses PostgreSQL (more standard,
                        more portable). Firebase is Google's,
                        slightly easier for total beginners.
                        Either is a reasonable choice — Supabase
                        is the more commonly recommended default
                        for new projects in 2025-2026.


  SYSTEM C — THE GENERATOR (backend logic)
  ------------------------------------------
  Core language    : JavaScript / TypeScript (Node.js)
                      Using the same language as the frontend
                      means your team doesn't need to context-
                      switch between two different programming
                      languages — a major efficiency win for a
                      small team.
  What it does     : Takes the structured project data (a JSON
                      object describing every element, its
                      position, color, animation, and text) and
                      programmatically writes out a real HTML
                      file — string templates, not magic.
  Where it runs    : A "serverless function" — a small piece of
                      backend code that runs on demand, instead
                      of needing a server running 24/7.
                      Options: Netlify Functions (pairs naturally
                      with Netlify hosting), or Supabase Edge
                      Functions if using Supabase for the database.


  SYSTEM D — THE PUBLISHER (hosting integration)
  -------------------------------------------------
  Service          : Netlify (their official API)
  Language         : JavaScript/TypeScript again — calling
                      Netlify's API is just sending an HTTP
                      request with the file attached, same
                      language as everything else.
  What it does     : Uploads the generated HTML file to Netlify,
                      Netlify hosts it and returns a live URL,
                      which gets shown to the user and saved
                      against their project record.


  SUMMARY — ONE LANGUAGE FAMILY FOR EVERYTHING
  -----------------------------------------------
  JavaScript / TypeScript covers all four systems:
  React (frontend) + Node.js (backend logic) + same language
  throughout. This is a deliberate, common choice for small
  teams — it means anyone on the team can technically read and
  contribute to any part of the codebase, instead of needing
  separate specialists for separate languages.


