----------------------------------------------------------------
5. THE CORE DATA STRUCTURE (what a "project" actually is)
----------------------------------------------------------------

Every project the user builds is, underneath everything, just
this kind of structured data. Understanding this is the single
most important concept in the whole system — once this exists,
the editor reads/writes it, the generator turns it into HTML,
and the database stores it.

  {
    "projectId": "abc123",
    "title": "Andrea's 18th Birthday",
    "theme": {
      "primaryColor": "#c9a84c",
      "backgroundColor": "#0d0d0d"
    },
    "elements": [
      {
        "id": "el-1",
        "type": "text",
        "content": "Andrea's 18th",
        "position": { "x": 50, "y": 100 },
        "animation": "fade-in"
      },
      {
        "id": "el-2",
        "type": "countdown",
        "targetDate": "2025-07-12T18:00:00",
        "position": { "x": 50, "y": 200 }
      },
      {
        "id": "el-3",
        "type": "button",
        "label": "RSVP now",
        "link": "#rsvp",
        "position": { "x": 50, "y": 400 }
      }
    ]
  }

This is what gets saved to the database, and this is what the
Generator (System C) reads to build the final HTML page.


----------------------------------------------------------------
6. TEAM ROLES — WHO YOU ACTUALLY NEED
----------------------------------------------------------------

This can realistically be built by 2-4 people. Here's the
breakdown by role, not headcount — one person can sometimes
cover two roles if they're skilled enough.

  ROLE 1 — FRONTEND DEVELOPER (most critical hire)
  ---------------------------------------------------
  Skills needed   : React, JavaScript/TypeScript, CSS,
                    drag-and-drop libraries
  Owns            : System A (the editor itself)
  Why critical    : This is the part the user actually sees and
                    touches. If this isn't good, nothing else
                    matters.

  ROLE 2 — BACKEND / FULL-STACK DEVELOPER
  ---------------------------------------------------
  Skills needed   : Node.js, JavaScript/TypeScript, REST APIs,
                    database experience (Supabase/Firebase or
                    SQL in general)
  Owns            : System B (database), System C (generator),
                    System D (Netlify publishing)
  Why critical    : This is the engineering-heavy plumbing that
                    makes "Get Link" actually work.

  ROLE 3 — UI/UX DESIGNER (can be you, or a hire)
  ---------------------------------------------------
  Skills needed   : Figma, understanding of usability for
                    non-technical users, your existing eye for
                    the Step Up visual style
  Owns            : What the editor itself looks like, what the
                    output templates look like, the overall
                    "feel" of using the product
  Why critical    : You already have this instinct — everything
                    we've built together proves it. This role
                    could stay yours even with a dev team.

  ROLE 4 — QA / TESTER (can start part-time, even you)
  ---------------------------------------------------
  Skills needed   : Patience, attention to detail, testing on
                    real phones and browsers
  Owns            : Making sure exported pages actually work on
                    real devices, catching bugs before users do
  Why critical    : An invitation that breaks on someone's phone
                    is the worst possible failure for this
                    product — it's the whole point.

  OPTIONAL ROLE 5 — PROJECT MANAGER (only needed once team grows)
  -------------------------------------------------------------
  Not needed for a team of 2-3. Worth adding only once you have
  4+ people and things start getting hard to track.


----------------------------------------------------------------
7. BUILD PHASES — REALISTIC ORDER
----------------------------------------------------------------

  PHASE 1 — Editor canvas only (no backend)
    Frontend dev builds: drag elements onto canvas, select and
    edit them, live preview. Runs entirely in the browser, no
    server needed yet. This alone is demoable and testable.

  PHASE 2 — Local save/load
    Add localStorage so a project survives a page refresh.
    Proves the data structure (Section 5) works in practice.

  PHASE 3 — The Generator
    Backend dev builds the JSON-to-HTML converter. Test it by
    manually feeding it sample project data and checking the
    output HTML actually works when opened in a browser.

  PHASE 4 — Real accounts + database
    Add Supabase/Firebase. Users can sign up, save projects
    permanently, and see a dashboard of their past projects.

  PHASE 5 — Netlify publishing
    Wire up the "Get Link" button to actually call the Generator,
    then the Netlify API, and return a real working URL.

  PHASE 6 — Polish + launch
    Real animation presets, more element types, mobile-friendly
    editor itself, onboarding for first-time users.


----------------------------------------------------------------
8. WHAT YOU SHOULD PERSONALLY STUDY FIRST
----------------------------------------------------------------

Even hiring a team, understanding the basics means you can
direct the project intelligently instead of being talked over.
Suggested order, easiest to hardest:

  1. HTML/CSS basics            - you already know this well
                                    from everything we've built
  2. JavaScript fundamentals     - variables, functions, arrays,
                                    objects (this maps directly
                                    to Section 5's data structure)
  3. What React actually is      - components, props, state
                                    (conceptual understanding is
                                    enough — you don't need to
                                    write production React)
  4. What an API call is         - the concept of one program
                                    asking another program for
                                    something over the internet
                                    (this is literally what
                                    "calling the Netlify API"
                                    means)
  5. What a database is          - tables, rows, basic concept
                                    of storing/retrieving records

Free resources: freeCodeCamp.org and The Odin Project both
cover this exact path, free, structured, beginner-friendly.


----------------------------------------------------------------
9. ROUGH COST REALITY (for planning, not exact quotes)
----------------------------------------------------------------

  Free while building/testing:
    - Netlify (hosting + functions) — free tier
    - Supabase or Firebase (database) — free tier
    - All the code/tools themselves — free, open source

  Costs that show up once real:
    - Developer salaries/rates — the actual biggest cost
    - Eventually: Netlify/Supabase paid tiers once usage scales
    - Possibly: a custom domain for the editor itself

The infrastructure itself stays nearly free for a long time.
The real cost of this project is development time/talent, not
hosting or tools.


